mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: packed with UPX
Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Adversaries may modify file time attributes to hide new or changes to existing files.
Adversaries may delete or modify artifacts generated within systems to remove evidence of their presence or hinder defenses.
Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.
Adversaries may perform software packing or virtual machine software protection to conceal their code.
May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis
Sample is packed with UPX
Binary contains a suspicious time stamp
Sample is packed with UPX
Queries the cryptographic machine GUID
Reads software policies
Reads the hosts file
Performs DNS lookups
Posts data to webserver
Performs DNS lookups
Posts data to webserver
Uses a known web browser user agent for HTTP communication
Creates a DirectInput object (often for capturing keystrokes)
May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)

signature_matches.name: packed with UPX
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: packed with UPX
    namespace: anti-analysis/packer/upx
    authors:
      - william.ballenthin@mandiant.com
    scopes:
      static: file
      dynamic: file
    att&ck:
      - Defense Evasion::Obfuscated Files or Information::Software Packing [T1027.002]
    mbc:
      - Anti-Static Analysis::Software Packing::UPX [F0001.008]
    examples:
      - CD2CBA9E6313E8DF2C1273593E649682
      - Practical Malware Analysis Lab 01-02.exe_:0x0401000
  features:
    - or:
      - and:
        - format: pe
        - or:
          - section: UPX0
          - section: UPX1
      - and:
        - format: elf
        - or:
          - string: "UPX!"

signature_matches.name: (internal) packer file limitation
signature_matches.description:
internal/limitation/static : This sample appears to be packed.

Packed samples have often been obfuscated to hide their logic.
capa cannot handle obfuscation well using static analysis. This means the results may be misleading or incomplete.
If possible, you should try to unpack this input file before analyzing it with capa.
Alternatively, run the sample in a supported sandbox and invoke capa against the report to obtain dynamic analysis results.
signature_matches.rule_src:
rule:
  meta:
    name: (internal) packer file limitation
    namespace: internal/limitation/static
    authors:
      - william.ballenthin@mandiant.com
    description: |
      This sample appears to be packed.

      Packed samples have often been obfuscated to hide their logic.
      capa cannot handle obfuscation well using static analysis. This means the results may be misleading or incomplete.
      If possible, you should try to unpack this input file before analyzing it with capa.
      Alternatively, run the sample in a supported sandbox and invoke capa against the report to obtain dynamic analysis results.
    scopes:
      static: file
      dynamic: file
    examples:
      - CD2CBA9E6313E8DF2C1273593E649682
  features:
    - or:
      - match: anti-analysis/packer

T1070.description: Adversaries may delete or modify artifacts generated within systems to remove evidence of their presence or hinder defenses.

T1027.description: Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.

T1497.description: May sleep (evasive loops) to hinder dynamic analysis

T1056.description: Creates a DirectInput object (often for capturing keystrokes)

T1518.001.description: May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)
